<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-04-30T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-04-30T13:00:00-05:00" n="1096" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1096">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.11/304.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">American
                                    Ambassador</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-30T13:00:00-05:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">April 30, 1912—1 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Your April 27, 11 a.m. The Department will let the British and French
                            warships arrive at Mexican ports before passing finally upon the
                            question of the advisability of sending an American warship.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>